title: For Sale:  1917 Lee Enfield .303 SHTLE Peddle Scheme Rifle
location: Clayton, NC, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
I have for sale one 1917 Lee Enfield SHTLE .303 SSA marked, British Peddle Scheme Rifle. Long story short, Standard Small Arms (SSA) was a commercial manufacturer that was established to challenge production cost/numbers during WWI in England. SSA was never successful in meeting manufacturing goals, and became more of a primary contractor supplying parts such a receivers, barrels, trigger housings, etc which were assembled in the Enfield bayonet shop. SSA later became NRF (National Rifle Factory) in 1918 after being taken over by the British government.

I purchased this rifle several years back from my local gunsmith, as it had been left by a previous customer years back to pay a bill.  When I purchased it, the stock had all been butchered and sporterized. I replaced all the furniture with a stock set from a DP rifle, but used as much as the original parts as possible.  The bluing doesn't look all original, hard to tell so it may have been blued sometime in the past.  There is pitting on the whole exterior of the barrel. Rifling is good, with some minor pitting.  

I am asking $200 for the rifle. Hate to sell since it's almost 100 years old, but I am tired of moving it around the safe. I can best be reached by phone (text preferred) at REDACTED

I have for sale a rather hard to find Winchester commemorative rifle that was made for the Canadian market and is not very common in the States. This is a Model 94 "CHEROKEE CARBINE". These were manufactured in 1978 in memory of the Cherokee Indian Nation. Chambered for the .30-30 cartridge, it wears a 20" barrel with iron sights. The receiver, butt plate, barrel bands, and magazine cap are all gold plated. The receiver is engraved with an Indian portrait with scroll work on the right and an Indian scout leading a covered wagon and the legend "Trail of Tears-1839" on the left. title: For Sale:  NIB/UNFIRED CENTENNIAL '66 RIFLE & CARBINE 30-30s
postcontent:
I have for sale an Awesome 2-gun set of Centennial '66s Rifle and Carbine. 


 1966 was the Winchester Repeating Arms Company's 100th year of operation. To commemorate this occasion, Winchester produced a run of fancy Model 94 rifles. These were based on post 1964 Model 94's actions with a gold plated receiver and for end cap, brass "rifle" (curved) butt plate, saddle ring, and a heavy octagon barrel with a full length magazine that was nicely polished and deeply blued. The straight hand stock was select walnut. All were in caliber .30-30 Winchester. 


 There were rifle (26") and carbine (20") barrel lengths, and sets of rifle and carbines were also offered. The point to all of the gold and brass was to make the 1966 Centennial reminiscent of the brass framed Winchester 1866 "Yellow Boy" rifle that was Winchester's first product. 


 These Centennial '66 rifles and carbines generally showed a high order of fit and finish. The receiver was 24 carat gold plated inside and out, so they were pretty with the action open, too. Here are the basic specifications of the Centennial '66 Rifle: 


 -NEW IN THE BOX UNFIRED 


 -GOLD plated receiver

title: For Sale/Trade:  1907 Remington Autoloading Shotgun Pre Model 11 (Browning A5)
postcontent:
Remington Autoloading Shotgun manufactured in 1907. This is the first USA manufacture of the Browning Auto 5 shotgun licensed to FN in Belgium. Also known as the Pre Model 11, it came about when John Browning licensed USA production of his patent to Remington in order to get around US tariffs on the Belgian made Auto 5. It was produced from 1905-10 and this is a number matching, five digit (38XXX), third year production firearm. Wood is possibly original, but unsure. Usual splits in the forearm. Pachymar recoil pad is not original.  Cycles flawlessly!

Open to trades, prefer cash or Sig 2022 9mm.
